ce:section.ce:para:
Fluorine doping can be used to adjust the physicochemical and optical properties of CDs. Dong et al. [160] prepared F-CDs via a one-pot solvothermal route with 1,2-diamino-4,5-difluorobenzene as fluorine source. Fluorine doping can red-shift the emission wavelength by at least 50 nm (Fig. 9
                           ). Meanwhile, the QY in F-CDs is also higher than that in undoped CDs, indicating that fluorine doping can be used to improve the luminescence efficiency of CDs. Very recently, Ye et al. [81] produced F-CDs with red fluorescence using microwave-assisted method. The red-shifted emission can be attributed to the extent of the π-electron system due to fluorine doping. In other words, an increase in the extent of the π-electron system will narrow the energy gap of the π-π* transitions and cause a small energy gap between surface states [162]. As a result, this lowers the energy level and leads to red-shifted fluorescence (Fig. 10
                           ).

CDs usually exhibit fluorescence quenching in powder samples that is directly attributed into a re-absorption effect, electronic quenching at the excited state, or an induced photothermal effect [41]. However, Si-CDs show excellent and stable solid-state fluorescence that compensates self-quenching in solid state. Liu et al. [166] prepared Si-CDs with stable solid-state red fluorescence for the first time (Fig. 11
                           ). Interestingly, Si-CDs in aqueous solution showed bright blue fluorescence due to the high-density zigzag edge structure. The extra-large red-shifted emission from Si-CDs in the liquid phase or solid state is ascribed to resonance energy transfer, which usually occurs over a small interparticle distance within R0 (Fig. 12
                           ). Moreover, dual-fluorescence composites with blue and orange emission can be prepared by integrating Si-CDs with starch. Because of their unique properties, Si-CDs-based composites with dual-fluorescence can be used for oxygen sensing and white light-emitting diodes.

Mn(II) doping can be used to tune the fluorescent emission from CDs by narrowing the band gap of CDs, leading to emission at longer wavelengths. Feng’s group [207] showed that yellow fluorescence from Mn-doped CDs (Mn-CDs) is dominated by core state emission. This arises because the band gap of Mn-CDs narrows down in the presence of intrinsic defects due to Mn(II) doping and subsequent formation of metal-coordinating functional knots. The strong interaction between metal and ligand orbitals in functional knots greatly enhances radiative recombination of excitons from the carbon core, together with the highly weak surface state fluorescence (Fig. 20
                           ). In addition, the formation of Mn(II)-induced functional knots within the carbon core causes excitation-independent emission due to the formation of a relatively uniform energy level. Regarding undoped CDs (i.e., PCDs), both surface state and core state emission contribute to the cyan-bluish fluorescence from PCDs (Fig. 20). Furthermore, Feng’s group [55] proposed an intraparticle Förster resonance energy transfer (IPFRET) system produced intrinsically in Mn-CDs. These Mn-CDs exhibit unique dual emission consisting of fluorophore-related emission (FE) and Mn(II)-functionalized core-related emission (ME). Energy transfer can occur from a fluorophore-like donor to metal-related acceptor due to overlap between the FE and ME-corresponding excitation spectrum in aqueous solution. Meanwhile, solvent relaxation (SR) occurs in a partial metal-coordinated sp2-network rather than at surface traps. Importantly, IPFRET in Mn-CDs can be finely tuned by adjusting the solvent polarity on metal-related ME acceptors, which modifies the fluorescent emission from Mn-CDs (Fig. 21
                           ).
